In deontic logic: **O(seek_consent B act)** — it is obligatory that seeking consent occurs before acting.

Using temporal deontic notation: □(act(a,t) → ◇(seek_consent(a,t') ∧ t' < t)) — necessarily, any action at time t requires that consent-seeking occurred at some prior t'.

In SDL (Standard Deontic Logic) with a permission operator: ¬P(act) until grant(consent), i.e., acting is forbidden unless consent has been obtained, making consent a precondition that transforms the deontic status of the action from prohibited to permitted.

The operator is an **obligation** (O), not merely permission (P) or prohibition (F): O(∀a∀x: before(do(a,x), seek_consent(a,x))), binding on all agents a for all actions x.
